s 'barbarian' territories as they separated from the Roman Empire.By applying the techniques of linguistic anthropology to the pre-history of medicine, anatomical knowledge, and law, Lisi Oliver has produced a remarkable study that sheds new light on early Germanic conceptions of the body in terms of medical value, physiological function, psychological worth, and social significance.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aHuman bodyxLaw and legislationzEuropexHistoryyTo 1500. 0aLaw, GermanicxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aPersonal injurieszEuropexHistoryyTo 1500. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144266192940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442661929423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442661929.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK